  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Does my duck have hypothermia?",
  "response": "To determine if your duck might have hypothermia, you should look for the following signs:\n\n1. **Lethargy**: If your duck seems unusually tired or unresponsive.\n2. **Shivering**: Ducks may shiver to generate heat when they are cold.\n3. **Cold to the Touch**: If the duck's body feels unusually cold, especially the feet and legs.\n4. **Huddled Posture**: Ducks may huddle together or tuck their heads under their wings to conserve heat.\n5. **Difficulty Moving**: Hypothermic ducks may have trouble walking or standing.\n\nIf you suspect your duck has hypothermia, take the following steps:\n\n1. **Move to a Warm Environment**: Bring your duck to a warm, sheltered area immediately.\n2. **Provide Heat**: Use a heat lamp or a warm water bottle wrapped in a towel to gently warm your duck. Be careful not to overheat.\n3. **Offer Warm Fluids**: If your duck is conscious and able to drink, offer warm (not hot) water or electrolytes.\n4. **Monitor and Seek Veterinary Care**: Keep a close eye on your duck's condition and contact a veterinarian experienced with poultry for further advice and treatment.\n\nPreventing hypothermia is also important. Ensure your ducks have access to a draft-free shelter, dry bedding, and that they are not exposed to cold, wet conditions for extended periods.",
